What is Food Grade Sodium Dithionite?
Food Grade Sodium Dithionite is a white, crystalline, finely powdered chemical that dissolves readily in water. Its primary function is to act as a reducing agent, breaking down complex pigment molecules into soluble compounds and thereby neutralizing discoloration. In addition, it serves as an antioxidant, neutralizing free radicals that can degrade quality and nutritional value in food matrices. The agent is approved for use in a wide array of food categories by major international regulation bodies, including the U.S. FDA and the European Food Safety Authority, thereby reinforcing its status as a trusted additive in the industry.
The agent’s adoption spans multiple product lines that demand stringent color control. In candied fruits and dried fruit products, sodium dithionite removes the natural brown pigment caused by Maillard reactions, enabling a bright, appealing visual appeal that directly influences consumer purchase decisions. In noodle manufacturing, the agent helps in maintaining a paler appearance and improves the overall quality of the final product.
